Grotesque style male head, broken from a figure, with a deep furrow on the brow and the hair and the ears barely indicated; a tightly woven wreath rings the head, which was made separately from the body, with a short peg for insertion into it. It is solid; probably from a two-piece mould, with the wreath perhaps added after removal from the mould. Orange-brown Nile silt with a grey core, frequent fine gold mica, quartz and rare white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of woman with basket on head. Head broken from a figure of a kanephoros: a woman with wavy hair, which is parted in the middle with locks falling towards her shoulder, and who wears a narrow fillet. Her right hand survives to support a tall cylindrical basket on top of her head; incuse details of the basket are well shown. The back is plain. Hollow, from two-piece mould, with traces of paint: orange-pink on her hair and hand; cream and pink on the basket. Brown Nile silt, with abundant fine gold mica, quartz and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure group fragment of dwarf and leg of larger figure. Dwarf walking to right, or perhaps seated, his face to the front; he is largely bald, with hair surviving at his left temple. His left hand is raised to his mouth and his right hand rests on his buttocks. He is walking from, or seated against, the left lower leg of a much larger figure, the leg apparently bare, but traces of drapery survive on each side. Hollow, from two-piece mould, with traces of a white dressing on the leg of the larger figure and pink paint on the dwarf’s upper thigh and the drapery. Red-brown Nile silt with a red zone and grey core, abundant fine gold mica, quartz and white inclusions.

description.value: Fragment of terracotta group.  Part of a group of a theatrical nature, with Omphale shown as an obese naked woman, standing on a low plinth. Her hair is parted in the centre and she wears a cap or veil over her head. She carries Herakles’ lion skin draped over her left arm, the head of the lion hanging by her side and its tail dangling below; Herakles’ club is held in the crook of her left arm. Omphale has broken away from another figure, presumably Herakles, standing on her right side, his arm round her shoulders and his hand resting on her upper left arm. The back is plain, with the top edge of a rectangular vent.  Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous brown Nile silt with a reddish core; the front is covered with a buff-coloured surface.

description.value: Terracotta figure of Amazon with shield.  An Amazon standing in an offensive/defensive position, with a small shield held to her left side, and her right arm drawn back, the hand pierced to hold a separately made weapon, now lost. The shield, rather than a true Amazonian pelta, is of truncated Gaulish oval shape, with a central spine and an oval boss with flared plates. She wears a short chiton, girded below the breasts, with an overfall; her right breast is uncovered. She also has greaves and boots. She stands on a plain, flat-fronted plinth, which has an inserted floor. At the back her drapery is summarily treated, and a queue of hair or the lower end of a helmet-crest is indicated below the break of the head.  Two-piece mould. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt, with some minute traces of pink paint (probably rose madder); the shield boss and elsewhere appear to have very small areas of a white dressing. The boots are painted red.

description.value: Terracotta figure of Young Pan with Eros. A young Pan carrying Eros on his back. Pan leans to his left and looks upwards; he has goat’s legs and supports Eros, who looks over his right shoulder, by reaching behind with his left arm. Eros, who is wreathed, grips Pan’s right hand and upper arm, which is bent at the elbow and raised to his right shoulder. Pan has wild curly hair and is probably horned: the left horn a mere bump, the right one damaged (however, the latter may be part of Eros’ left wing, which is ill-defined). Summary treatment at the rear. Solid, from two-piece mould, with thick overall white dressing, thicker at the front than the back. Pan’s flesh is painted pink, his hairy legs are worn, with traces of white coating and some brown paint; Eros’ flesh is left white, and his wings are painted blue. Fine pale brown clay with some mica.

description.value: Terracotta figure of dwarf-like male celebrant.  A bearded dwarf standing on a plain-faced plinth, leaning with his right hand on a sealed amphora on a wooden stand. He wears a short skirt-like garment from which his phallus emerges to touch the ground. His right leg is raised to rest his foot on the glans of the phallus; his left arm is akimbo with his hand on his waist. The navel protrudes. He is balding (a line of hair is shown in a summary manner round the back of his head) and wears a garland across his head above his brow, with a bloom below it on each side above his ears; a ribbon holds lotus buds to the top of his head. There is very little modelling at the back, which is pierced by a circular vent.   Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt. There are remains of a thick white dressing, mainly on the front; traces of red paint on the left wrist and left foot.

description.value:
Fragmentary sandstone female figure, the lower body and part of the head now missing.

The figure wears a long striated wig with a broad section of hair at the back, the full form of the style at the top of the head now lost. A taller portion of the stone on the left side could possibly indicate that she wore a crown or headdress. The facial features are also obscured. Across the surviving portion of the upper body are straps across the chest delineating her dress, which was likely a long tight-fitting style. On the reverse is a portion of a slim back-pillar which meets the ends of the wig.

In addition to the loss of much of the figure, there are various small chips to the wig and upper body. The figure is now attached to a modern rectangular base.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of Isis riding a horse. Isis riding astride a stallion rearing to right, its forelegs off the ground. The goddess,  whose body is twisted to front, with her leg bent sharply at the knee, wears a short-sleeved tunic of uncertain length, with probable indications of an ‘Isis knot’ between the breasts. Her head is lost, but locks and a wreath fall to her left shoulder; one lock remains on the right shoulder. She probably held a palm branch in her right hand, but the stem only remains. A wide fillet extends in a curve from her wreath to her left hand, which appears to hold a small, uncertain object, possibly a pot. There seems little doubt that she not only had a palm branch, but also a large headdress of wreaths and a crown. The horse apparently has no harness. The group stands on a rectangular plinth with mouldings top and bottom; it is inset at each end. The back is plain, with a circular vent. Hollow, from two-piece mould. Matt red-brown slip on the front, with areas of a white dressing also on the front, particularly on the deity’s clothing; some pink paint on the horse; one hoof, at least, appears to be painted black. Brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica, common rounded quartz and white inclusions.

description.value: Pink limestone seated figure of a royal male subject in mummified form, the head and upper part of the throne now lost.  The figure is depicted sitting on a high-backed throne, with the body and feet enveloped in clothing and only the hands exposed. At the neckline is a shallow v-shaped line that extends across the chest. Both arms are crossed over the body, and in each hand he holds a crook and flail. The details of both of these implements and the figure’s hands have been executed to a high quality. Traces of the royal head and the outline of a tall crown are preserved on the front of the throne. At the top right corner of the throne are the remains of a serekh hieroglyph sign, the top portion partly damaged. There are no traces of further text on the reverse or sides of the throne.
